<body>
    <h1>What is a Skill?</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h1 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-WhatisaSkill?">What is a Skill?</h1>
<p>A short primer on the most useful idea in Claude =E2=80=94 and the one m=
ost people skip.</p>
<p>Owner: Charlie Delamare<br>
Audience: Anyone at Mews who's set up Claude and wants to get more out of i=
t<br>
Estimated reading time: 5 minutes</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Inonesentence">In one sentence</h2>
<p>A <strong>skill</strong> is a saved set of instructions that teaches Cla=
ude how to do a specific task =E2=80=94 once. After that, you (or anyone el=
se) can use it forever.</p>
<p>Think of it as the difference between <strong>explaining how to make you=
r coffee</strong> every single morning vs. <strong>writing it down once and=
 pinning it to the fridge</strong>. Skills are the pinned note.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-What'sactuallyinaskill">What's actually in a skill<=
/h2>
<p>A skill is a small, reusable bundle. At its simplest it's just:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>name</strong> (e.g. "How I write on Slack")</p></li>
<li>
<p>A <strong>description</strong> of when Claude should use it (so Claude k=
nows when to reach for it)</p></li>
<li>
<p>The <strong>instructions</strong> themselves =E2=80=94 written in plain =
English</p></li>
</ul>
<p>A more complex skill can also include:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Example inputs and outputs</strong> ("when the input looks like =
X, the output should look like Y")</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Reference files</strong> (templates, glossaries, brand guideline=
s, sample documents)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Scripts</strong> that Claude can run as part of executing the sk=
ill (for the technical end)</p></li>
</ul>
<p>But you don't need any of the fancy stuff to start. A 10-line plain-Engl=
ish skill is genuinely useful.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Whyskillsmatter">Why skills matter</h2>
<p>Three reasons:</p>
<p><strong>1. Consistency.</strong> If you write a skill for "how to send a=
 customer-facing email", every email Claude drafts for you afterwards sound=
s the same. No more "this one's a bit too formal, this one's a bit too casu=
al".</p>
<p><strong>2. Speed.</strong> You stop re-explaining context every time. In=
stead of writing a 200-word prompt explaining what your weekly update shoul=
d look like, you say "use the weekly update skill" and you're done.</p>
<p><strong>3. Sharing.</strong> A skill is a single file. You can hand it t=
o a colleague, drop it in the team folder, paste it into Slack. They get in=
stant access to the same way of working as you, without having to rebuild t=
he prompt from scratch.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Arealexample">A real example</h2>
<p>Here's what a basic skill looks like in practice =E2=80=94 this one teac=
hes Claude how to write a Monday morning standup-style update:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">NAME: M=
onday morning update

WHEN TO USE: When I ask for "my weekly update", "Monday update", or
"what should I tell the team this week".

INSTRUCTIONS:
- Pull my calendar from last week and the week ahead.
- Pull any commits / PRs I made (if relevant) and any Confluence
  edits.
- Write a Slack-ready post in this format:
    Last week:
    - 3 bullet points, each starting with a verb
    This week:
    - 3 bullet points
    Heads-up:
    - Anything blocking me, anything the team should know
- Use my voice (see "How I write on Slack" skill)
- Keep it under 150 words total.
- No emoji.</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>That's it. Once that skill exists, every Monday I just say "do my weekly=
 update" and out comes something that sounds like me, every time.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Howtocreateaskill">How to create a skill</h2>
<p>Three options, in increasing order of effort:</p>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-OptionA=E2=80=94AskClaudetomakeoneforyou(easiest)">=
Option A =E2=80=94 Ask Claude to make one for you (easiest)</h3>
<p>You can literally just say:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Create a skill called "How I write on Slack" that captures my tone, sent=
ence length, where I use emoji, and how I open and close messages. Use my l=
ast month of Slack messages as the source.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Claude will read the source material, draft the skill, save it, and tell=
 you what it called it. Done. This is how 80% of useful skills get made.</p=
>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-OptionB=E2=80=94Writeityourselfinchat">Option B =E2=
=80=94 Write it yourself in chat</h3>
<p>If you already know what the skill should do, paste the instructions int=
o Chat and ask Claude to save them as a skill:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Save the following as a skill called "Customer follow-up email":</p>
<p>[your instructions here]</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-OptionC=E2=80=94WriteaSKILL.mdfiledirectly">Option =
C =E2=80=94 Write a <code>SKILL.md</code> file directly</h3>
<p>For more advanced skills (with reference files, multi-step logic, etc.) =
you can create a folder containing a <code>SKILL.md</code> file plus any su=
pporting assets, and drop it into Claude's skills folder. This is how the M=
ews-specific skills in Charlie's library are structured.</p>
<p>The <code>SKILL.md</code> file looks like:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">---
name: skill-name
description: When Claude should use this skill =E2=80=94 write this careful=
ly,
  it's how Claude decides whether to reach for it.
---

# Skill Name

Plain-English instructions go here. Use headings, lists, examples =E2=80=94
whatever makes the instructions clear.</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>If you want to write skills this way, the <code>skill-creator</code> ski=
ll (already installed) will guide you through it =E2=80=94 just ask Claude =
to "use the skill creator to help me build a new skill."</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Howtoinstallaskillsomeoneelsemade">How to install a=
 skill someone else made</h2>
<p><strong>If it's a single </strong><code>SKILL.md</code> or a folder with=
 one inside:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Drag the file or folder into a Chat window</p></li>
<li>
<p>Ask Claude: <strong>"Install this as a skill"</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Claude will copy it to the right place and confirm</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>If it's bundled as a plugin or </strong><code>.mcpb</code>:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Double-click the file (or use <strong>Settings =E2=86=92 Extensions =E2=
=86=92 Advanced =E2=86=92 Install Extension</strong>)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Restart Claude</p></li>
<li>
<p>The skill is now available</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>If it's a folder in SharePoint/Drive:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Download the folder to your machine</p></li>
<li>
<p>Drag it into Chat</p></li>
<li>
<p>Ask Claude to install it</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Charlie'sskillslibrary">Charlie's skills library</h=
2>
<p>A growing collection of pre-made skills, ready to copy and use:</p>
<p><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://mewssystems-my.sharepoint.com=
/:f:/g/personal/charlie_delamare_mews_com/IgA1QzKGAx_gTakh0aR6Y6mrAQKoxvkPy=
LXj0vL4bgUHXPc?e=3DSPlEgv" rel=3D"nofollow"><strong>SharePoint folder =E2=
=86=92</strong></a></p>
<p>If you build a skill that you think others would benefit from, drop it i=
n there. The more people who contribute, the better the library gets.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Skillsworthbuilding">Skills worth building</h2>
<p>A starting list of skills that are worth the 10 minutes it takes to crea=
te them. Steal any of these.</p>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Communication">Communication</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>How I write on Slack</strong> =E2=80=94 your voice, sentence len=
gth, where you use emoji, how you open and close</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>How I write emails</strong> =E2=80=94 same idea, but for email</=
p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Customer follow-up email</strong> =E2=80=94 the exact structure =
you use after a customer call</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Internal announcement</strong> =E2=80=94 the format for posting =
in #team-* channels</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Meeting recap</strong> =E2=80=94 turn raw notes into a tidy summ=
ary you can paste back into the channel</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Meetings">Meetings</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Prep me for a customer call</strong> =E2=80=94 pull from Outlook=
, Salesforce, Gong, write a one-pager</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Prep me for a 1:1</strong> =E2=80=94 pull last week's calendar, =
any Slack DMs, write 3 talking points</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Notes after a 1:1</strong> =E2=80=94 turn rough notes into actio=
n items, save to Confluence</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Weekly leadership update</strong> =E2=80=94 pull from your own c=
alendar / commits / Slack, format for the leadership channel</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Recurringtasks">Recurring tasks</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Monday morning update</strong> =E2=80=94 your weekly standup pos=
t (see example above)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>End of quarter recap</strong> =E2=80=94 pull from Salesforce, Go=
ng, Slack =E2=80=94 what did the team ship, who closed what, what to call o=
ut</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>New starter welcome message</strong> =E2=80=94 the message you a=
lways send when someone joins your team</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Birthday / anniversary message</strong> =E2=80=94 the kind of wa=
rm one-liner you keep meaning to write but always forget</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Customer-facing">Customer-facing</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Discovery call prep</strong> =E2=80=94 given a company name, pul=
l what we know from Salesforce + Common Room + LinkedIn, write a brief</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p><strong>Demo prep</strong> =E2=80=94 given a Salesforce account, pull th=
e deal stage, last interactions, and known pain points</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Renewal / expansion prep</strong> =E2=80=94 pull from Mews PMS d=
ata, recent Gong calls, recent support tickets</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Internaladmin">Internal admin</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Expense submission</strong> =E2=80=94 given a receipt, format it=
 the way our finance system wants</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Translate this for marketing</strong> =E2=80=94 apply Mews' tone=
-of-voice + brand-glossary to a piece of text</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Polish my Confluence page</strong> =E2=80=94 given rough notes, =
structure them with proper headings, summary up top, action items at the bo=
ttom</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Threerulesofthumbwhenwritingaskill">Three rules of =
thumb when writing a skill</h2>
<p><strong>1. The description matters more than you think.</strong> Claude =
uses it to decide whether to reach for the skill. Be specific about <em>whe=
n</em> it should fire (e.g. "when I ask for my weekly update or my Monday u=
pdate"), not just what it does.</p>
<p><strong>2. Show, don't just tell.</strong> A 5-line example output is wo=
rth 50 lines of instructions. If you can paste an example of what "good" lo=
oks like, do it.</p>
<p><strong>3. Start simple, evolve it.</strong> Your first skill won't be p=
erfect. Use it for a week, notice the things you keep correcting Claude on,=
 and add those rules to the skill. By week three it'll be exactly right.</p=
>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"WhatisaSkill?-Gotquestions?">Got questions?</h2>
<p>Ask Claude =E2=80=94 seriously, "help me build a skill for X" is one of =
the things it's best at.</p>
<p>Or ping me on Slack: <strong>@Charlie Delamare</strong>.<br>
Or post in <strong>#ran-ai</strong> so the team can see the answer.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
